Varanids are one of the more high profile, well studied and widely recognised groups of lizards in the world (e.g.
King & Green 1993 ;
Vincent & Wilson 1999 ;
Eidenmüller 2007 ). Australia is a global centre of varanid lizard diversity (
Pianka et al.2004 ); however taxonomic activity over the last decade has focused on varanid taxa distributed across the islands of Indonesia and the Philippines (e.g.
Ziegler et al.2007 ;
Welton et al.2010 ;
Koch et al.2010 a
;
Koch et al.2013 ). Thus, while the total number of recognised varanid species has increased to over 70 in recent years (
Koch et al.2010 b
), the total number of Australian species has remained relatively stable at around 27 or 28 (
Wilson & Swan 2013 ). The last major alpha-taxonomic work on Australian Varanidae was published over thirty years ago (
Storr 1980 ). This focused on Western Australian species and included descriptions of five new taxa: V. kingorum , V. panoptes panoptes , V. panoptes rubidus , V. pilbarensis and V. storri ocreatus . Since this revision, two additional species of Australian varanid have been described: V. keithhornei Wells & Wellington, 1985 and V. b u s h i Aplin, Fitch & King, 2006 . Other significant contributions to the Australian varanid diversity include confirmation that V. doreanus occurs on Cape York (
Ziegler et al.2001 ; S. Wilson pers. comm.), and V. prasinus on the Torres Strait islands (
Wilson 1996 ;
Clarke 2004 ). There however remain unresolved taxonomic issues amongst Australian varanids, mostly involving widespread taxa that show extensive morphological and/or phylogenetic divergence across their distributions (
Fuller et al.1998 ;
Ast 2001 ; Fitch et al.2006 ). The Pilbara region in Western Australia is one of Australia’s herpetological ‘hotspots’ with many endemic lizards and snakes (
How & Cowan 2006 ;
Powney et al.2010 ;
Bush & Maryan 2011 ;
Doughty et al.2011 a
). The varanid fauna of this region is no exception and includes 10 species (over one-third of the total Australian species diversity). While most Varanus species found in the Pilbara are widespread across much of arid and semiarid Australia , there are two endemic species. Varanus bushi is a small arboreal species widespread in woodlands across the Pilbara, and closely related to two widely distributed arid zone taxa, V. caudolineatus and V. gilleni (
Aplin et al.2006 )
. The other endemic varanid to the Pilbara is V. pilbarensis , a morphologically distinctive and phylogenetically divergent saxicolous species (Fitch et al.2006 ). As presently defined, V. pilbarensis is found on rocky ranges and outcrops both to the north (Chichester Range) and south (Hamersley Range) of the Fortescue River Basin in the Pilbara region. The original description of this species was based on nine specimens, eight of which came from north of the Fortescue River Basin. On recent biological surveys by Biologic Environmental Survey in the southern Pilbara (specifically the eastern Hamersley Range) in 2011 , it was observed that V. pilbarensis from these sites differed noticeably in colour pattern from northern populations. Further observations during other recent surveys also suggested that two distinct colour forms existed. We present an investigation of the mitochondrial and morphological variation within V. pilbarensis . Based on the results of this investigation we restrict V. pilbarensis to the northern Pilbara, and describe the southern populations as a new species.

Genetics. Our final alignment of sequence data was 663 base pairs (bp) long; 600 bp from the 5 ' end of the
ND 4 gene and 63 bp of tRNAHis . We found no insertion or deletion events or misplaced stop codons, suggesting that the sequence amplified is not paralogous. Amongst samples of V. pilbarensis103 sites were variable, and of these 90 were parsimony informative. No species was recovered as sister to V. pilbarensis (and we included all potential candidates based on the sampling in Fitch et al.2006 ). A clade including V. pilbarensis and seven other mediumsized saxicolous and arboreal species was supported in maximum likelihood bootstrap analysis (ML scores of 100 ;
). While our sampling of varanids was incomplete, this monophyletic lineage, containing V . glauerti , V . glebopalma , V . mitchelli , V . scalaris , V . semiremex , V. timorensis and V . tristis was also supported by analysis presented in Fitch et al.2006 that included all recognized Australian varanid species (not all outgroups included in this study are shown in
).

The monophyly of all specimens currently referred to V . pilbarensis was strongly supported. Within V. pilbarensis we identified two divergent and strongly supported clades distributed to the north and south of the Fortescue River Basin (mean uncorrected divergence 10.2 %, range 9.7–11.2 %). Within the southern clade we found very little evidence of significant geographic structure (mean uncorrected divergence 0.5 %, range 0.0– 1.4 %) over a distance spanning ~ 300 km from Newman in the east to Mount Rica in the west (
). In contrast, within the northern clade there was evidence of more significant structure from east to west (mean uncorrected divergence 4.1 %, range 0.0– 6.6 %) over a distance spanning ~ 400 km from Meentheena in the east to Pannawonica in the west (
). The deepest divergence within this northern clade was between a western lineage including samples from the Burrup Peninsula and around Pannawonica, and a lineage distributed widely through to the east. There was also evidence of further genetic structuring within this western lineage of the northern clade although geographic sampling was insufficient to assess this in detail.

Colouration
. In preservative many aspects of colouration fade considerably. The dark tail colouration however preserves well. Consistent strong banding extending the length of the tail is diagnostic of specimens from the Chichester and other northern ranges while specimens from the Hamersley Range have tails with scattered dark brown spots that (at most) formed very indistinct bands concentrated towards the anterior half. Faint large, pale grey ocelli were also more apparent on the dorsum of preserved specimens from the northern Pilbara (

, 

). In specimens from the Hamersley Range the ocelli were concentrated on the limbs (

, 

).

Taxonomic conclusions. The combination of molecular and morphological data indicates the existence of two geographically discrete lineages characterised by differences in colouration on the dorsum, limbs and tail (
,
). Each lineage spans an east-west distribution of over 300 km (Fig. 2 ) and based on the available preserved material, at a number of sites they come into close geographic proximity: within ~ 60 km in the western Pilbara ( WAM R 164579 from 8.5 km NE Mount Rica v. WAM R 110941 from 44 km W Pannawonica) and ~ 60 km in the central Pilbara ( WAM R 14901 from Dales Gorge v. WAM R 39782 from the Cockeraga River) but are not obviously intermediate. Field observations of the two forms have also been made in closer proximity ~ 40 km in the eastern Chichester Range at Roy Hill ( 22 º 12 ' 40 "S 119 º04' 13 "E
) and Hamersley Range at Marillana ( 22 º 12 ' 40 "S 119 º00' 22 "E
) (Fig. 2 ). While further sampling may reveal contact zones, the two forms are diagnosable and genetically divergent over their respective distributions. We consider this evidence consistent with the presence of two evolutionary distinct and historically independent lineages (species).

