sec.p:
The Pilbara region of Western Australia is geologically distinctive, including some of the most ancient rock formations on earth (
McKenzie et al.2009 ) and has a diverse and highly endemic reptile fauna (Pepper et al.2010 ;
Pepper et al.2013 a
;
Doughty et al.2011 a
). Varanus hamersleyensis sp. nov. adds yet another endemic lizard species, and raises the number of endemic varanid species to three, the others being V. pilbarensis (saxicolous) and V. bushi (arboreal).

Taxonomic investigations continue to reveal that species diversity in many groups of Australian lizards is higher than widely recognised. However, while there are exceptions, most of this diversity is concentrated in relatively small, non-descript species (e.g.
Horner 2007 ;
Smith & Adams 2007 ;
Oliver et al.2010 ). In contrast, varanids include many of the world’s largest lizards and are amongst the most high profile and recognisable components of the Australian herpetofauna. There is however evidence of significant diversity within a number of other nominal varanid species from northern Australia and further research may lead to the recognition of additional new species (
Ast 2001 ; Fitch et al.2006 ). The description of a relatively spectacular new Australian varanid, and the potential existence of additional unrecognised taxa amongst this distinctive and iconic lineage, underlines the fact that we are still far from completing the species inventory of the diverse Australian lizard fauna.

